      "text": "In a German main clause, the conjugated verb is always the second element. This is known as Verbzweitstellung (V2 rule). While English usually follows a strict 'Subject-Verb' order, German is more flexible about what comes first.",
      "title": "The Verb-Second Rule"
    },
    {
      "text": "If you start a sentence with anything other than the subject (like a time expression or a location), the verb stays in the second position, and the subject must move to the third position. This is called 'inverted' word order.",
      "title": "Subject-Verb Inversion"
    }
  ],
